article.headline: New Jersey runs to eighth straight home win

images.name: Kidd_Jason 020320 inline
images.caption: Jason Kidd was two rebounds shy of his second straight triple-double.

article.linkText: Kidd, Nets cool off Blazers to extend home streak
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The belief that the officials cost them a game in Cleveland 24 hours earlier had one positive effect for the New Jersey Nets: It fired them up for the Portland Trail Blazers. Jason Kidd had 28 points, 11 assists and eight rebounds and the angry Nets won their eighth straight home game by cooling off the Trail Blazers 97-82 Wednesday night. "This was a game where we could have easily had our doors blown off and blamed it on last night," said Kidd, who shot 11-of-19 from the field. "This shows the character of these guys. Through adversity we stepped up and answered the call." Less than two hours before the game, Nets coach Byron Scott and president Rod Thorn were still lamenting the team's 100-97 loss at Cleveland. After tying the game with five-tenths of a second to play on a 3-pointer by Keith Van Horn, the Nets watched in disbelief as Lamond Murray made a 3-pointer at the buzzer after he caught an inbounds pass, squared himself and shot -- all within that same five-tenths of a second. The Nets blamed the loss on the officials not starting the clock on time. "It gave us a little extra momentum coming into the game," said Kerry Kittles, who added 18 points. "Guys were a little hungry. You could see it in their eyes before the game, that we were going to win." Keith Van Horn added 14 points as the Nets handed the Trail Blazers only their second loss in 17 games. Rasheed Wallace, who played only seven minutes in the first half after picking up three fouls, led Portland with 17 points. Damon Stoudamire added 14 and Ruben Patterson had 13 for the Trail Blazers, who shot only 41.5 percent from the field. "Having Rasheed out of the game was tough, but we just got beat," Stoudamire said. "They played a good game and we just didn't come out and match their energy." The Nets never let it come down to a last shot against Portland. Kidd scored the final 10 points in a 15-0 second quarter run that staked New Jersey to a 48-40 halftime lead. A 3-pointer by Wallace had Portland within 69-64 entering the final quarter, but the Nets blew the game open with a 20-4 spurt in a quarter that featured a number of Kidd highlights. One was a backdoor layup from Kenyon Martin; another was a behind-the-back pass that set up a layup by Richard Jefferson. "I think we were a little ticked off after last night," Scott said. "We came back and played the best team in the league at this time. They are the hottest team in the league. We did a heck of a job of taking it right at them." Kidd came within two rebounds of his 47th career triple-double and his second in as many nights. The victory was the Nets' 43rd of the season, 17 more than they had last year. It tied Scott with John Calipari for engineering the biggest single-season turnaround in team history. Game notes
Nets backup point guard Lucious Harris had surgery to repair a broken facial bone Wednesday. It's not known how long he'll be sidelined. ... Wallace took Portland's first six second-half shots, making three. ... Portland had won five straight vs. New Jersey. ... This was only the fifth time in 24 games that Portland has lost with all its players healthy. ... Dale Davis returned from a two-game suspension and had five points and six rebounds in 33 minutes.
